task_description:
In the  experiment, each participant is given 36 different proposals to respond to. Each is designated by a trial number in the data set This gives 36 instances for the learnable parameters to be trained. There is also a pretask where the participant finds a number of tokens that correspond to their contribution to the group. This is designated by the variable "token_self". The other variable, "token_opp", is the number of tokens found the opponent's and represents the opoonents contribution to the shared pot that will be later divided by the opponent.

Note that in each trial there is a variable amount of money in the combined earning, so that two equal split_self variables do not represent the same "fairness".

Below is the description of each variable in the dataset, which will be followed by information about the data type of the variable:

trial_type = how much was the contribution [1 = equal, 2 = opponent more, 3 = participant more]
trial_role = the role of the participant [1 = responder, 2 = proposer]
token_opp = number of tokens found by the opponent
token_self = number of tokens found by the participant
combined_earning = amount of money earned in total (note that each token found is £3)
split_opp = the proposed share of the opponent (in £)
split_self = the proposed share for the participant (in £)
splitperc_opp = same but in %
split_perc_self = same but in %
accept = whether the participant responded accept (1) or reject (0)
accepted_amount = if accepted, what is the amount gain (in £)
accepted_perc = same as above but in %
proposed_perc = when participant is the proposer, what is the % proposed to the opponent

Step-by-step reasoning:

1. Key psychological mechanisms:
 • Fairness norm sensitivity: participants form a fairness norm based on their token contributions relative to those of their opponent. This norm can be computed as the proportional share of the combined earning the participant “deserves.”
 • Inequity aversion: responders penalize offers that fall below their normative fair share.
 • Self-interest: responders value monetary gain, here measured by the proposed split for themselves (split_self).

2. Interactions:
 • The participant computes a norm: fair_share = (token_self/(token_self+token_opp)) * combined_earning.
 • They then compare the received offer (split_self) to this norm.
 • If the offer is below their fairness norm, the utility is penalized (via a quadratic penalty); if the offer meets or exceeds the norm, no penalty is applied.
 • An additional baseline bias is included to capture any extra inclination toward acceptance.

3. Mathematical form:
 • The utility, U, of accepting the offer is modeled as:
  U = beta + split_self − lambda * [max(0, fair_share − split_self)]²,
  with fair_share = (token_self/(token_self + token_opp)) * combined_earning.

4. Learnable parameters:
 • beta: a baseline bias parameter.
 • lambda: a fairness sensitivity parameter expressing the degree to which deviations below the norm reduce utility.
 Both parameters have explicit finite bounds (beta ∈ [–100, 100] and lambda ∈ [0, 100]) to aid in parameter recovery.

5. Mapping to observable behavior:
 • The dependent variable (split_self) and token variables from the dataset plug into the computation of fair_share.
 • The resulting utility value U is then used (after transformation) to predict the probability of acceptance in each trial.
 • When U is negative (indicating a strongly unfair or insufficient offer), the response is less likely to be accepted.

Step-by-step reasoning:

1. Key psychological mechanisms:
 • Fairness norm sensitivity: participants form a fairness norm based on their token contributions relative to those of their opponent. This norm can be computed as the proportional share of the combined earning the participant “deserves.”
 • Inequity aversion: responders penalize offers that fall below their normative fair share.
 • Self-interest: responders value monetary gain, here measured by the proposed split for themselves (split_self).

2. Interactions:
 • The participant computes a norm: fair_share = (token_self/(token_self+token_opp)) * combined_earning.
 • They then compare the received offer (split_self) to this norm.
 • If the offer is below their fairness norm, the utility is penalized (via a quadratic penalty); if the offer meets or exceeds the norm, no penalty is applied.
 • An additional baseline bias is included to capture any extra inclination toward acceptance.

3. Mathematical form:
 • The utility, U, of accepting the offer is modeled as:
  U = beta + split_self − lambda * [max(0, fair_share − split_self)]²,
  with fair_share = (token_self/(token_self + token_opp)) * combined_earning.

4. Learnable parameters:
 • beta: a baseline bias parameter.
 • lambda: a fairness sensitivity parameter expressing the degree to which deviations below the norm reduce utility.
 Both parameters have explicit finite bounds (beta ∈ [–100, 100] and lambda ∈ [0, 100]) to aid in parameter recovery.

5. Mapping to observable behavior:
 • The dependent variable (split_self) and token variables from the dataset plug into the computation of fair_share.
 • The resulting utility value U is then used (after transformation) to predict the probability of acceptance in each trial.
 • When U is negative (indicating a strongly unfair or insufficient offer), the response is less likely to be accepted.
